<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-06-06T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-06-06T18:00:00-05:00" n="610" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d610">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">561.311F1/96: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                            to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-06-06T19:00:00-04:00">June 6, 1933—7
                                p.m.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>151. For Morgenthau from Wallace. Your 166, June 2. We can probably exercise
                        sufficient control of exports for the purposes of international agreement
                        under the existing authority of Section 8, subsection 2, of the farm act.
                        [Wallace.]</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>